====================
Circuit Breaker
====================

Definition
----------
Circuit Breaker is a fault tolerance design pattern used in microservices to prevent cascading failures.  
When a service fails repeatedly, the circuit breaker stops calling that service temporarily and returns a fallback response.

It acts like an electrical circuit breaker that stops the flow of current when a fault occurs.

--------------------------------------------------

Problem Without Circuit Breaker
-------------------------------
In microservices architecture, services depend on other services.

Example
Client -> API Gateway -> Product Service -> Review Service

If the Review Service becomes slow or unavailable:

• Product Service keeps waiting for response  
• Threads remain blocked  
• Response time increases  
• System resources get exhausted  
• Other services may also start failing  

This situation can lead to cascading failures across the entire system.

--------------------------------------------------

Solution Using Circuit Breaker
------------------------------
Circuit Breaker monitors service calls and failure rates.

If failures exceed a configured threshold:

• Circuit Breaker opens  
• Requests to the failing service are stopped  
• Fallback response is returned immediately  
• System remains stable  

After a configured time, the circuit breaker allows a few test requests to check if the service has recovered.

--------------------------------------------------

Circuit Breaker States
----------------------

1. Closed State

This is the normal state.

• All requests are allowed to pass to the downstream service  
• Success and failure of requests are recorded  
• If failure rate exceeds the threshold, the circuit breaker moves to Open state  

--------------------------------------------------

2. Open State

In this state, requests to the failing service are blocked.

• No calls are sent to the downstream service  
• Fallback response is returned immediately  
• Prevents system overload  

After a configured wait time, the circuit breaker moves to Half Open state.

--------------------------------------------------

3. Half Open State

In this state, limited test requests are allowed.

• If test requests succeed → circuit closes again  
• If test requests fail → circuit returns to open state  

This helps determine whether the service has recovered.

--------------------------------------------------

==========================================
Resilience4j Circuit Breaker Configuration
==========================================

Configuration
-------------
resilience4j:
  circuitbreaker:
    instances:
      reviews-service:
        registerHealthIndicator: true
        slidingWindowSize: 10
        minimumNumberOfCalls: 5
        permittedNumberOfCallsHalfOpenState: 3
        automaticTransitionFromOpenToHalfOpenEnabled: true
        waitDurationInOpenState: 10s
        failureRateThreshold: 50
        eventConsumerBufferSize: 10
        recordExceptions:
          - org.springframework.web.client.HttpServerErrorException
          - java.io.IOException
          - java.util.concurrent.TimeoutException
          - feign.FeignException
        ignoredExceptions:
          - java.lang.IllegalArgumentException


Overview
--------
This configuration defines a Circuit Breaker using Resilience4j for the service named "reviews-service".

The circuit breaker monitors calls made to the Reviews Service.  
If too many failures occur, it temporarily stops calling the service and returns a fallback response.


Circuit Breaker Instance
------------------------
reviews-service

This is the name of the circuit breaker instance.

It is usually the same name used in the annotation:

@CircuitBreaker(name = "reviews-service", fallbackMethod = "fallbackMethod")


Property Explanations
---------------------


registerHealthIndicator
-----------------------
registerHealthIndicator: true

This enables health monitoring for the circuit breaker.

Spring Boot Actuator can show the circuit breaker status such as:
- CLOSED
- OPEN
- HALF_OPEN


slidingWindowSize
-----------------
slidingWindowSize: 10

This defines the number of recent calls used to calculate the failure rate.

Example:
The circuit breaker will analyze the last 10 requests.


minimumNumberOfCalls
--------------------
minimumNumberOfCalls: 5

The circuit breaker will not calculate the failure rate until at least 5 requests are made.

Example:
If only 3 calls happened, the circuit breaker will not open yet.


failureRateThreshold
--------------------
failureRateThreshold: 50

This defines the percentage of failures required to open the circuit.

Example:

Total calls = 10  
Failures = 5  

Failure rate = 50%

Since the threshold is 50%, the circuit breaker will open.


waitDurationInOpenState
-----------------------
waitDurationInOpenState: 10s

When the circuit breaker enters OPEN state, it waits 10 seconds before trying again.

During these 10 seconds:
- No calls are sent to the Reviews Service
- Fallback response is returned immediately


permittedNumberOfCallsHalfOpenState
-----------------------------------
permittedNumberOfCallsHalfOpenState: 3

When the circuit breaker moves to HALF_OPEN state, it allows 3 test requests.

If those 3 requests succeed:
Circuit Breaker -> CLOSED

If those requests fail:
Circuit Breaker -> OPEN again


automaticTransitionFromOpenToHalfOpenEnabled
---------------------------------------------
automaticTransitionFromOpenToHalfOpenEnabled: true

This allows the circuit breaker to automatically move from OPEN state to HALF_OPEN after the wait time.


eventConsumerBufferSize
-----------------------
eventConsumerBufferSize: 10

This controls how many circuit breaker events are stored.

Examples of events:
- success
- failure
- state transition


recordExceptions
----------------
recordExceptions:
  - org.springframework.web.client.HttpServerErrorException
  - java.io.IOException
  - java.util.concurrent.TimeoutException
  - feign.FeignException

These exceptions will be counted as failures by the circuit breaker.

Example:
If a Feign client throws FeignException, the circuit breaker records it as a failure.


ignoredExceptions
-----------------
ignoredExceptions:
  - java.lang.IllegalArgumentException

These exceptions are ignored and will not affect the circuit breaker.

Example:
If IllegalArgumentException occurs, the circuit breaker will not treat it as a failure.


Request Flow Example
--------------------

Client
  |
  v
API Gateway
  |
  v
Product Service
  |
  v
Circuit Breaker
  |
  v
Reviews Service


Normal Scenario
---------------
Circuit Breaker State = CLOSED

Product Service calls Reviews Service normally.


Failure Scenario
----------------
If 5 out of 10 requests fail:

Failure Rate = 50%

Circuit Breaker → OPEN


Open State
----------
For the next 10 seconds:

Requests are NOT sent to Reviews Service.

Fallback response is returned.


Half Open State
---------------
After 10 seconds:

3 test requests are sent.

If successful → CLOSED  
If failed → OPEN again

Example Microservice Flow
-------------------------

Client
  |
  v
API Gateway
  |
  v
Product Service
  |
  v
Circuit Breaker
  |
  v
Review Service

If Review Service fails repeatedly:

Circuit Breaker opens and Product Service returns fallback response instead of calling the failing service.

--------------------------------------------------

Advantages
----------

• Prevents cascading failures  
• Improves system stability  
• Reduces response time during failures  
• Allows systems to recover automatically  
• Provides fallback responses for better user experience

--------------------------------------------------

Real World Example
------------------

E-commerce Application

Product Service -> fetch product details  
Review Service -> fetch product reviews  

If Review Service is down:

Without Circuit Breaker
Product Service waits and system becomes slow.

With Circuit Breaker
Product Service skips Review Service call and returns product details with empty reviews.

